00:23:33.510 --> 00:23:36.100 align:middle line:84%
for the HSP for a
really long time.

00:23:36.100 --> 00:23:38.100 align:middle line:84%
And so I would just go
through moments of having

00:23:38.100 --> 00:23:39.690 align:middle line:90%
meltdowns and breakdowns.

00:23:39.690 --> 00:23:41.520 align:middle line:84%
And I would keep them
private because I

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:43.380 align:middle line:90%
didn't want to be a bother.

00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:45.210 align:middle line:90%
But that was my way of doing it.

00:23:45.210 --> 00:23:47.410 align:middle line:84%
I'd go a month or
two really hard.

00:23:47.410 --> 00:23:49.322 align:middle line:10%
And then I would crash.

00:23:49.322 --> 00:23:51.030 align:middle line:10%
And there were times
where I didn't know,

00:23:51.030 --> 00:23:52.950 align:middle line:10%
I didn't have the
maturity or the experience

00:23:52.950 --> 00:23:56.130 align:middle line:10%
enough to create a day
or two after a show

00:23:56.130 --> 00:23:57.630 align:middle line:10%
or after a big event.

00:23:57.630 --> 00:23:59.342 align:middle line:84%
Oftentimes, I would
just careen right

00:23:59.342 --> 00:24:01.050 align:middle line:84%
into the next event
or the next interview

00:24:01.050 --> 00:24:03.780 align:middle line:84%
or the next show
or the next video.

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:06.000 align:middle line:90%
And it was hard on my body.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:11.280 align:middle line:84%
I developed a really fiery
version of work addiction

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:13.500 align:middle line:84%
that I've been in
recovery for a while.

00:24:13.500 --> 00:24:15.600 align:middle line:84%
And in being in recovery
for work addiction,

00:24:15.600 --> 00:24:17.820 align:middle line:84%
I have found myself
really caring

00:24:17.820 --> 00:24:19.860 align:middle line:84%
for this highly
sensitive part of me.

00:24:19.860 --> 00:24:22.560 align:middle line:10%
>> Alanis Wrote "That
I Would Be Good"

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:25.440 align:middle line:10%
as a reflection of her being
a highly sensitive person.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:27.606 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC - ALANIS MORISSETTE,
 "THAT I WOULD BE GOOD"]

00:24:27.606 --> 00:24:36.140 align:middle line:10%
>> (SINGING) That I would be
good, even if I did nothing.

00:24:36.140 --> 00:24:38.300 align:middle line:10%
I wrote "That I Would
Be Good in my closet,

00:24:38.300 --> 00:24:39.570 align:middle line:10%
because I was so overwhelmed.

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:41.480 align:middle line:10%
My home became this
Grand Central Station.

00:24:41.480 --> 00:24:45.380 align:middle line:10%
And I remember there having
been 10 people downstairs.

00:24:45.380 --> 00:24:47.450 align:middle line:84%
And so I hid in my
closet, of all places.

00:24:47.450 --> 00:24:51.290 align:middle line:84%
And I remember lighting a
candle on the floor in my closet

00:24:51.290 --> 00:24:53.780 align:middle line:84%
and writing "That I Would
Be Good" as a prayer,

00:24:53.780 --> 00:24:57.770 align:middle line:84%
like a meditation that I could
listen to that would soothe me

00:24:57.770 --> 00:25:00.560 align:middle line:84%
in times of overstimulation
and maxing out

00:25:00.560 --> 00:25:02.530 align:middle line:84%
and not having had enough
time alone or breaks.

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:05.730 align:middle line:90%


00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:08.922 align:middle line:84%
And it was just
like a gentle balm.

00:25:08.922 --> 00:25:13.220 align:middle line:10%
>> Overstimulation is a serious
disadvantage of the trait--

00:25:13.220 --> 00:25:14.780 align:middle line:10%
true.

00:25:14.780 --> 00:25:18.550 align:middle line:84%
But Alanis told us about
the emotional responsiveness

00:25:18.550 --> 00:25:22.540 align:middle line:84%
and empathy she can feel with
her highly sensitive audience

00:25:22.540 --> 00:25:25.615 align:middle line:84%
that makes her feel so
authentic as a performer.

00:25:25.615 --> 00:25:27.781 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - ALANIS MORISSETTE,
 "THAT I WOULD BE GOOD"]

00:25:27.781 --> 00:25:33.040 align:middle line:84%
>> (SINGING) That I would be
good, even if I did nothing.

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:36.256 align:middle line:90%


00:25:36.256 --> 00:25:37.880 align:middle line:84%
So there were some
songs that even when

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:40.421 align:middle line:84%
I would perform them on stage
around the planet when we would

00:25:40.421 --> 00:25:43.520 align:middle line:84%
tour, immediately the first
few chords would play,

00:25:43.520 --> 00:25:48.950 align:middle line:84%
and I would just feel this
huge relief wash over me.

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:51.740 align:middle line:84%
And I could just see
the sweet HSP faces.

00:25:51.740 --> 00:25:54.976 align:middle line:84%
A lot of them, a lot of the
HSPs are right up front.

00:25:54.976 --> 00:25:59.300 align:middle line:84%
And so there's a lot of
emotional crying and fervor

00:25:59.300 --> 00:26:02.040 align:middle line:90%
and passion.

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:03.832 align:middle line:84%
And we would just be
married to each other.

00:26:03.832 --> 00:26:07.550 align:middle line:84%
I would be a lot of
physical catharsis on stage.

00:26:07.550 --> 00:26:11.120 align:middle line:84%
And then I would see the effect
of it in the people's faces

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:11.920 align:middle line:90%
in the audience.

00:26:11.920 --> 00:26:13.400 align:middle line:84%
So it was really
gratifying in that way.

00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:15.566 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - ALANIS MORISSETTE,
 "THAT I WOULD BE GOOD"]

00:26:15.566 --> 00:26:17.446 align:middle line:84%
>> (SINGING) That
I would be good,

00:26:17.446 --> 00:26:22.156 align:middle line:84%
e if I lost my
hair and my youth.

00:26:22.156 --> 00:26:25.680 align:middle line:84%
>> If you think being emotional
means being irrational,

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:29.430 align:middle line:84%
actually, the latest thinking
is that emotions generally lead

00:26:29.430 --> 00:26:32.880 align:middle line:84%
to better thinking, because
we only think thoroughly about

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:36.275 align:middle line:90%
something we care about.

00:26:36.275 --> 00:26:39.920 align:middle line:84%
>> Dr. Robert Levenson at
the University of California,

00:26:39.920 --> 00:26:43.405 align:middle line:84%
Berkeley, is well known for
his research on emotion.

00:26:43.405 --> 00:26:45.560 align:middle line:10%
>> One of the things if
you study emotion that

00:26:45.560 --> 00:26:49.280 align:middle line:10%
you're struck by is just
how different people are

00:26:49.280 --> 00:26:53.540 align:middle line:10%
in the size of the emotions they
have and the frequency at which

00:26:53.540 --> 00:26:55.100 align:middle line:10%
they become emotional.

00:26:55.100 --> 00:26:59.480 align:middle line:10%
>> One of the things that highly
sensitive people report is that

00:26:59.480 --> 00:27:00.950 align:middle line:10%
they cry easily.

00:27:00.950 --> 00:27:03.080 align:middle line:84%
Now other people
also cry easily,

00:27:03.080 --> 00:27:06.590 align:middle line:84%
but it seems to be in general
more true of highly sensitive.

00:27:06.590 --> 00:27:07.980 align:middle line:90%
Why would that be?

00:27:07.980 --> 00:27:10.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you're processing
information more thoroughly,

00:27:10.790 --> 00:27:13.096 align:middle line:84%
then the same thing
that might not quite

00:27:13.096 --> 00:27:15.470 align:middle line:84%
make someone else cry because
they're not quite attending

00:27:15.470 --> 00:27:18.600 align:middle line:84%
to it in as much detail is going
to make the highly sensitive

00:27:18.600 --> 00:27:19.400 align:middle line:90%
person cry.

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:23.600 align:middle line:10%
>> These findings also show that
highly sensitive people show

00:27:23.600 --> 00:27:27.950 align:middle line:10%
greater activation in areas that
are associated with empathy.

00:27:27.950 --> 00:27:34.010 align:middle line:10%
So in at least 20 or
30 studies of empathy,

00:27:34.010 --> 00:27:36.830 align:middle line:10%
people showed activation
in certain areas

00:27:36.830 --> 00:27:38.930 align:middle line:10%
that highly sensitive
people are also

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:42.560 align:middle line:10%
engaging to a greater degree
in response to their partners

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:45.080 align:middle line:10%
and to stranger's emotions.

00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:49.280 align:middle line:84%
>> When I walk into a room, I
know what everyone is feeling.

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:51.220 align:middle line:84%
I know if someone
has had a bad day,

00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:54.860 align:middle line:84%
I know if someone is
arguing with their wife.

00:27:54.860 --> 00:27:56.960 align:middle line:90%
It can be overwhelming.

00:27:56.960 --> 00:28:00.800 align:middle line:10%
And at a period of time, I
couldn't leave my house at all

00:28:00.800 --> 00:28:03.470 align:middle line:10%
when I lived in Los Angeles
because I'd walk out my door

00:28:03.470 --> 00:28:06.100 align:middle line:10%
and feel the feelings
of eight million people.

00:28:06.100 --> 00:28:08.470 align:middle line:84%
And so I'd run
back into my house.

00:28:08.470 --> 00:28:13.040 align:middle line:84%
But I really, really love
that I noticed things

00:28:13.040 --> 00:28:14.360 align:middle line:90%
that other people don't notice.

00:28:14.360 --> 00:28:18.440 align:middle line:84%
It helps me being an antenna for
the world through my writing.

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:21.040 align:middle line:84%
I know what's going on and
what people need to hear,

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:22.290 align:middle line:90%
and then I can write about it.

00:28:22.290 --> 00:28:26.600 align:middle line:84%
So I've turned it sort of
from a curse and a bad trait

00:28:26.600 --> 00:28:29.075 align:middle line:84%
into something that is helpful
to myself and to others.

00:28:29.075 --> 00:28:38.162 align:middle line:90%


00:28:38.162 --> 00:28:41.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Empathy means we can
understand what the other

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:44.780 align:middle line:84%
person is feeling
and be supportive.

00:28:44.780 --> 00:28:47.870 align:middle line:84%
We can also use empathy
to help ourselves,

00:28:47.870 --> 00:28:51.260 align:middle line:84%
maybe to develop our
professional reputation

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:53.960 align:middle line:84%
by sensing, for example,
what our clients

00:28:53.960 --> 00:28:58.640 align:middle line:84%
or students or patients
need, even before they do.

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:02.090 align:middle line:10%
>> Extensive brain imaging
conducted by Jadzia

00:29:02.090 --> 00:29:05.120 align:middle line:10%
Jagiellowicz during her
doctoral studies at Stony Brook

00:29:05.120 --> 00:29:09.050 align:middle line:10%
University and published in
"Social Cognitive and Affective

00:29:09.050 --> 00:29:12.080 align:middle line:10%
Neuroscience" show that
the areas of the brain

00:29:12.080 --> 00:29:16.130 align:middle line:10%
for understanding subtle cues
are more active in sensitive

00:29:16.130 --> 00:29:17.830 align:middle line:10%
than non-sensitive persons.

00:29:17.830 --> 00:29:24.290 align:middle line:10%
>> What this study means is that
highly sensitive people notice

00:29:24.290 --> 00:29:27.720 align:middle line:10%
more about the
world they live in.

00:29:27.720 --> 00:29:31.910 align:middle line:84%
But the key thing is not
just that they notice more,

00:29:31.910 --> 00:29:36.260 align:middle line:84%
they take what they
notice and they combine it

00:29:36.260 --> 00:29:40.070 align:middle line:84%
with information that they've
noticed all their life.

00:29:40.070 --> 00:29:43.490 align:middle line:84%
So because they've noticed
more all their life,

00:29:43.490 --> 00:29:47.900 align:middle line:84%
and because they're able to
combine all that information,

00:29:47.900 --> 00:29:52.340 align:middle line:84%
they often come up
with unique new ideas.

00:29:52.340 --> 00:29:57.020 align:middle line:84%
>> Combining ideas in novel ways
is the essence of creativity.

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:00.770 align:middle line:10%
Even experiences while young,
such as with different animals,

00:30:00.770 --> 00:30:02.690 align:middle line:10%
may lead later to
creative insights

00:30:02.690 --> 00:30:05.900 align:middle line:10%
about all animals and
their temperaments.

00:30:05.900 --> 00:30:08.300 align:middle line:84%
Or, combining novel
ideas might bring

00:30:08.300 --> 00:30:10.700 align:middle line:84%
about new research
breakthroughs,

00:30:10.700 --> 00:30:15.230 align:middle line:84%
revolutionary art, or
world-changing insights.

00:30:15.230 --> 00:30:17.450 align:middle line:10%
We are not saying that all
creative people are highly

00:30:17.450 --> 00:30:20.690 align:middle line:10%
sensitive, but surely the
qualities we see in them do

00:30:20.690 --> 00:30:24.170 align:middle line:10%
contribute substantially
to creativity.

00:30:24.170 --> 00:30:26.600 align:middle line:84%
Another striking
finding was that there

00:30:26.600 --> 00:30:30.820 align:middle line:84%
was more activity for sensitive
people in the insula, part

00:30:30.820 --> 00:30:34.240 align:middle line:84%
of the brain often called
the seat of consciousness,

00:30:34.240 --> 00:30:36.520 align:middle line:84%
because it brings
together all of our inner

00:30:36.520 --> 00:30:37.930 align:middle line:90%
and outer experiences.

00:30:37.930 --> 00:30:42.160 align:middle line:10%
>> Highly sensitive individuals,
they're engaging the insula

00:30:42.160 --> 00:30:46.060 align:middle line:10%
to a greater extent because
in some ways it's like

00:30:46.060 --> 00:30:47.410 align:middle line:10%
they're more aware.

00:30:47.410 --> 00:30:50.980 align:middle line:10%
And this is in line with a
lot of the other research

00:30:50.980 --> 00:30:54.200 align:middle line:10%
and theory on sensory
processing sensitivity,

00:30:54.200 --> 00:30:58.030 align:middle line:10%
suggesting that highly
sensitive people are more aware

00:30:58.030 --> 00:30:58.830 align:middle line:10%
of others.

00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:00.640 align:middle line:84%
They are more aware
of the subtleties

00:31:00.640 --> 00:31:01.855 align:middle line:90%
in their environment.

00:31:01.855 --> 00:31:04.630 align:middle line:84%
>> These four qualities
we just explored--

00:31:04.630 --> 00:31:09.040 align:middle line:84%
depth of processing, being
easily overstimulated,

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:12.130 align:middle line:84%
being more emotionally
responsive,

00:31:12.130 --> 00:31:14.620 align:middle line:84%
and sensing the subtle
in the environment--

00:31:14.620 --> 00:31:18.280 align:middle line:84%
they add up to highly
sensitive people,

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:22.210 align:middle line:84%
especially in childhood, being
more affected by everything

00:31:22.210 --> 00:31:25.000 align:middle line:84%
that happens to them,
not just bad things,

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:26.170 align:middle line:90%
but good things too.

00:31:26.170 --> 00:31:30.660 align:middle line:90%


00:31:30.660 --> 00:31:33.760 align:middle line:84%
And these three
lines of research--

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:36.530 align:middle line:84%
mine, Jay Belsky
and Michael Pluess,

00:31:36.530 --> 00:31:38.930 align:middle line:84%
and Tom Boyce and
Bruce Ellis, we've

00:31:38.930 --> 00:31:44.750 align:middle line:84%
all converged on the same idea
of this wonderful trait that's

00:31:44.750 --> 00:31:47.960 align:middle line:84%
underneath the hood, that
can't be seen easily.

00:31:47.960 --> 00:31:52.040 align:middle line:84%
So it's not been described that
much by the general public.

00:31:52.040 --> 00:31:53.810 align:middle line:84%
You can't look at
someone and say, oh,

00:31:53.810 --> 00:31:56.300 align:middle line:84%
that person is sensitive
and that person is not.

00:31:56.300 --> 00:31:59.140 align:middle line:84%
Now people can
begin to understand

00:31:59.140 --> 00:32:02.480 align:middle line:84%
a child or a parent or a
friend or a spouse who's

00:32:02.480 --> 00:32:05.220 align:middle line:84%
highly sensitive, but they
didn't understand at first.

00:32:05.220 --> 00:32:12.490 align:middle line:90%


00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:15.850 align:middle line:84%
Jay Belsky and Michael Pluess
came up with this phrase--

00:32:15.850 --> 00:32:17.710 align:middle line:90%
differential susceptibility.

00:32:17.710 --> 00:32:21.880 align:middle line:10%
>> Differential susceptibility
is a fairly new concept that

00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:25.030 align:middle line:10%
refers to individual
differences in how we respond

00:32:25.030 --> 00:32:27.760 align:middle line:10%
to the environments
that we are exposed to.

00:32:27.760 --> 00:32:31.150 align:middle line:10%
Susceptibility is a fancy
word for sensitivity.

00:32:31.150 --> 00:32:33.430 align:middle line:10%
So basically it
refers to the notion

00:32:33.430 --> 00:32:36.100 align:middle line:10%
that some people are more
sensitive to experiences

00:32:36.100 --> 00:32:37.480 align:middle line:10%
they meet than other people.

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:41.380 align:middle line:10%
Environmental sensitivity is one
of the most fundamental traits

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:44.390 align:middle line:10%
found in humans,
but in many species.

00:32:44.390 --> 00:32:48.110 align:middle line:84%
And it's so fundamental that we
don't even think much about it.

00:32:48.110 --> 00:32:50.620 align:middle line:84%
But most of the concepts
we look at that focus

00:32:50.620 --> 00:32:52.650 align:middle line:84%
on individual differences
contain the notion

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:54.400 align:middle line:84%
that some people are
more affected by what

00:32:54.400 --> 00:32:56.200 align:middle line:90%
they experience than others.

00:32:56.200 --> 00:32:58.780 align:middle line:84%
Hence, my conclusion
or proposition

00:32:58.780 --> 00:33:01.570 align:middle line:84%
is that people
differ fundamentally

00:33:01.570 --> 00:33:05.050 align:middle line:84%
in how they perceive and
process environmental features,

00:33:05.050 --> 00:33:07.270 align:middle line:84%
with some being
generally more and some

00:33:07.270 --> 00:33:09.160 align:middle line:90%
being generally less sensitive.

00:33:09.160 --> 00:33:11.080 align:middle line:84%
Having a higher
degree of sensitivity

00:33:11.080 --> 00:33:13.900 align:middle line:84%
has advantages and
has disadvantages.

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:17.020 align:middle line:10%
>> Highly sensitive persons
process all experience more

00:33:17.020 --> 00:33:17.890 align:middle line:10%
deeply.

00:33:17.890 --> 00:33:21.550 align:middle line:10%
So when we have unsupportive
childhoods that are negative,

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:25.255 align:middle line:10%
when we didn't get the
responses from the parents

00:33:25.255 --> 00:33:27.880 align:middle line:10%
when we were very young, when we
didn't believe they would come

00:33:27.880 --> 00:33:32.900 align:middle line:10%
when we cried, when our
needs weren't taken care of,

00:33:32.900 --> 00:33:35.530 align:middle line:10%
that simply laid the
foundation for later life--

00:33:35.530 --> 00:33:38.960 align:middle line:10%
feeling more fearful, being
afraid to venture out and try

00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:40.270 align:middle line:10%
new things.

00:33:40.270 --> 00:33:42.280 align:middle line:10%
For those individuals
on the other side of it

00:33:42.280 --> 00:33:45.370 align:middle line:10%
who had supportive childhoods
where the parents provided

00:33:45.370 --> 00:33:47.620 align:middle line:10%
the nurturing,
provided the love,

00:33:47.620 --> 00:33:50.890 align:middle line:10%
provided the attention
that people need,

00:33:50.890 --> 00:33:53.420 align:middle line:10%
they had a strong
base to build on.

00:33:53.420 --> 00:33:55.240 align:middle line:84%
So when they ventured
out into life,

00:33:55.240 --> 00:33:58.010 align:middle line:84%
they felt more free,
more confident.

00:33:58.010 --> 00:33:59.650 align:middle line:84%
And when they faced
a setback, they

00:33:59.650 --> 00:34:02.070 align:middle line:84%
were more easily able
to bounce back from it.

00:34:02.070 --> 00:34:05.530 align:middle line:84%
>> So if someone is very
highly sensitive and is exposed

00:34:05.530 --> 00:34:09.100 align:middle line:84%
to very adverse environments,
then that person is more likely

00:34:09.100 --> 00:34:12.790 align:middle line:84%
to develop depression, because
that person is more affected

00:34:12.790 --> 00:34:15.400 align:middle line:90%
by that particular experience.

00:34:15.400 --> 00:34:21.250 align:middle line:10%
But the positive aspect is that
if they experience support from

00:34:21.250 --> 00:34:23.679 align:middle line:10%
their environment-- that could
be psychological therapy,

00:34:23.679 --> 00:34:25.840 align:middle line:10%
that could be social support--

00:34:25.840 --> 00:34:29.020 align:middle line:10%
they are more likely to
benefit from that support.

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:32.409 align:middle line:10%
>> So now my counsel is,
what you should tell people--

00:34:32.409 --> 00:34:35.670 align:middle line:10%
pediatricians, counselors,
neonatologists--

00:34:35.670 --> 00:34:37.850 align:middle line:10%
that some kids have more
difficult temperaments,

00:34:37.850 --> 00:34:41.909 align:middle line:10%
but they are much more
malleable clay in your hands.

00:34:41.909 --> 00:34:44.270 align:middle line:84%
They are going to
thrive and flourish

00:34:44.270 --> 00:34:46.810 align:middle line:84%
if you care for them
well, more so than others.

00:34:46.810 --> 00:34:49.330 align:middle line:84%
But they are going
to suffer and go down

00:34:49.330 --> 00:34:51.219 align:middle line:90%
if you care for them poorly.

00:34:51.219 --> 00:34:54.610 align:middle line:84%
So you are much more,
it seems, the conductor

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:59.320 align:middle line:84%
of this orchestra in those
cases than in other cases.

00:34:59.320 --> 00:35:00.460 align:middle line:90%
But will that get through?

00:35:00.460 --> 00:35:02.470 align:middle line:90%
Will people embrace this?

00:35:02.470 --> 00:35:03.425 align:middle line:90%
Time will tell.

00:35:03.425 --> 00:35:07.060 align:middle line:84%
>> Think deeply, think
deeply, feel things deeply.

00:35:07.060 --> 00:35:11.020 align:middle line:84%
>> Sometimes I will
and sometimes I won't.

00:35:11.020 --> 00:35:14.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Another school year, and you
had another teacher calling us

00:35:14.900 --> 00:35:16.900 align:middle line:84%
to tell us there's something
wrong with our son.

00:35:16.900 --> 00:35:20.160 align:middle line:90%


00:35:20.160 --> 00:35:24.254 align:middle line:84%
You've got to stop
overprotecting him, Pam.

00:35:24.254 --> 00:35:26.218 align:middle line:90%
I won't have it.

00:35:26.218 --> 00:35:29.210 align:middle line:84%
>> But I'm not
overprotecting him.

00:35:29.210 --> 00:35:32.240 align:middle line:90%
He's only seven years old.

00:35:32.240 --> 00:35:33.920 align:middle line:84%
Teacher just wants
us to go down there

00:35:33.920 --> 00:35:36.170 align:middle line:84%
and discuss a couple
things with us.

00:35:36.170 --> 00:35:39.380 align:middle line:84%
>> If Hank is being bullied, he
needs to stand up for himself.

00:35:39.380 --> 00:35:43.016 align:middle line:84%
>> Bill, she never said anything
about him being bullied.

00:35:43.016 --> 00:35:45.300 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, then what's
the problem this time?

00:35:45.300 --> 00:35:49.674 align:middle line:10%
>> I'd say that all the adult
highly sensitive people I know,

00:35:49.674 --> 00:35:52.090 align:middle line:10%
most of them will say their
parents didn't understand them

00:35:52.090 --> 00:35:55.065 align:middle line:10%
and that they're spending a
lot of time sorting that out.

00:35:55.065 --> 00:35:59.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I knew something was
up when my family was looking

00:35:59.500 --> 00:36:01.240 align:middle line:90%
at me somewhat strangely.

00:36:01.240 --> 00:36:04.157 align:middle line:84%
And I remember probably
about 10 years ago, my father

00:36:04.157 --> 00:36:06.490 align:middle line:84%
and I were sitting down, I
was hosting a show in Canada.

00:36:06.490 --> 00:36:09.820 align:middle line:84%
And he was having a moment, and
I was crying about something

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:13.000 align:middle line:84%
intense for me, which
he'd gotten used to,

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:14.170 align:middle line:90%
I suppose at that point.

00:36:14.170 --> 00:36:17.020 align:middle line:84%
He said to me, he said,
Alanis, I'm so sorry,

00:36:17.020 --> 00:36:19.340 align:middle line:84%
we just never really
knew what to do with you.

00:36:19.340 --> 00:36:20.140 align:middle line:90%
We were at a loss.

00:36:20.140 --> 00:36:22.306 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - ALANIS MORISSETTE,
 "THAT I WOULD BE GOOD"]

00:36:22.306 --> 00:36:27.475 align:middle line:84%
(SINGING) That I would be
loved, even when I numb myself.

00:36:27.475 --> 00:36:31.876 align:middle line:90%


00:36:31.876 --> 00:36:41.660 align:middle line:84%
That I would be good, even
when I am overwhelmed.

00:36:41.660 --> 00:36:44.990 align:middle line:84%
Something about that moment
in his authentic expression

00:36:44.990 --> 00:36:48.350 align:middle line:84%
of that to me, it
validated a lot

00:36:48.350 --> 00:36:52.760 align:middle line:84%
of my having felt
alone in a world

00:36:52.760 --> 00:36:55.430 align:middle line:84%
where I felt misperceived
and misunderstood.

00:36:55.430 --> 00:36:58.310 align:middle line:84%
And I knew that there were
a handful of things that,

00:36:58.310 --> 00:37:00.320 align:middle line:84%
if they were taken into
consideration, that I

00:37:00.320 --> 00:37:03.650 align:middle line:84%
would be my best self
really consistently.

00:37:03.650 --> 00:37:05.750 align:middle line:84%
And equally, if I were to
be in environments where

00:37:05.750 --> 00:37:08.420 align:middle line:84%
I was shamed for
what I now see is

00:37:08.420 --> 00:37:13.010 align:middle line:84%
talents and a gorgeous
trait, frankly,

00:37:13.010 --> 00:37:15.350 align:middle line:84%
had I been in environments
where it had been supported,

00:37:15.350 --> 00:37:16.933 align:middle line:84%
it would have been
a lot easier for me

00:37:16.933 --> 00:37:18.980 align:middle line:84%
and I wouldn't have
felt so shame-ridden.

00:37:18.980 --> 00:37:21.146 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - ALANIS MORISSETTE,
 "THAT I WOULD BE GOOD"]

00:37:21.146 --> 00:37:23.900 align:middle line:90%
(SINGING) That I would be good.

00:37:23.900 --> 00:37:27.800 align:middle line:84%
>> Alanis now enjoys advocating
for causes she has found to be

00:37:27.800 --> 00:37:29.760 align:middle line:90%
of central importance.

00:37:29.760 --> 00:37:31.830 align:middle line:90%
One is attachment parenting.

00:37:31.830 --> 00:37:35.720 align:middle line:84%
Also, because like her, her
son is highly sensitive,

00:37:35.720 --> 00:37:40.250 align:middle line:84%
she is deeply interested in
parenting sensitive children.

00:37:40.250 --> 00:37:43.090 align:middle line:84%
Alanis told me that she
and her husband, Souleye,

00:37:43.090 --> 00:37:45.470 align:middle line:84%
know that one key to
parenting their son,

00:37:45.470 --> 00:37:50.060 align:middle line:84%
Ever, is, in Alanis's words,
honoring his every feeling

00:37:50.060 --> 00:37:52.790 align:middle line:90%
and letting him feel it through.

00:37:52.790 --> 00:37:55.970 align:middle line:84%
Another is preventing his
becoming overstimulated.

00:37:55.970 --> 00:37:58.540 align:middle line:84%
If Alanis and Ever
both need down time,

00:37:58.540 --> 00:38:01.310 align:middle line:84%
then Souleye, not having
the trait himself,

00:38:01.310 --> 00:38:02.730 align:middle line:90%
can readily take over--

00:38:02.730 --> 00:38:03.530 align:middle line:90%
teamwork.

00:38:03.530 --> 00:38:07.994 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - ALANIS MORISSETTE,
 "THAT I WOULD BE GOOD"]

00:38:07.994 --> 00:38:14.940 align:middle line:90%


00:38:14.940 --> 00:38:18.780 align:middle line:84%
Overstimulation can lead to all
kinds of problems in children--

00:38:18.780 --> 00:38:20.400 align:middle line:90%
irritation and even tantrums.

00:38:20.400 --> 00:38:23.215 align:middle line:90%
>> Do you want me to carry you?

00:38:23.215 --> 00:38:28.600 align:middle line:84%
>> I would throw these tantrums
as a kid where I would just be

00:38:28.600 --> 00:38:29.400 align:middle line:90%
so overwhelmed.

00:38:29.400 --> 00:38:32.640 align:middle line:10%
And there were points where I
would be on the ground crying,

00:38:32.640 --> 00:38:34.124 align:middle line:10%
freaking out all the time.

00:38:34.124 --> 00:38:36.540 align:middle line:10%
>> There's a lot of parents
out there that would be really

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:40.680 align:middle line:10%
embarrassed by that behavior
where their child is fine one

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:43.200 align:middle line:10%
minute and the next minute
they're freaking out

00:38:43.200 --> 00:38:45.030 align:middle line:10%
on the ground,
crying, screaming.

00:38:45.030 --> 00:38:47.310 align:middle line:84%
So instead of
responding to the fact

00:38:47.310 --> 00:38:49.560 align:middle line:84%
that, oh, she's just
overwhelmed, this is too much,

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:51.862 align:middle line:84%
there's too much
information coming in,

00:38:51.862 --> 00:38:53.820 align:middle line:84%
there's too much sight,
there's too much sound,

00:38:53.820 --> 00:38:55.920 align:middle line:84%
there's too much
texture, there's just

00:38:55.920 --> 00:38:58.680 align:middle line:84%
too much stimulation,
they see their child

00:38:58.680 --> 00:39:00.360 align:middle line:90%
as all of a sudden becoming bad.

00:39:00.360 --> 00:39:02.520 align:middle line:84%
They discipline them,
they're embarrassed.

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:04.470 align:middle line:90%
They might get a spanking.

00:39:04.470 --> 00:39:07.860 align:middle line:84%
All unnecessarily if they
knew that their child was

00:39:07.860 --> 00:39:10.036 align:middle line:90%
a highly sensitive person.

00:39:10.036 --> 00:39:13.770 align:middle line:84%
>> Of course, it's always true
that parents should set limits

00:39:13.770 --> 00:39:15.630 align:middle line:90%
with any child.

00:39:15.630 --> 00:39:18.510 align:middle line:84%
But we all learn better when in
our optimal state of arousal,

00:39:18.510 --> 00:39:21.450 align:middle line:90%
neither under or overstimulated.

00:39:21.450 --> 00:39:24.000 align:middle line:84%
A stern message may help
to get a less sensitive

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:27.770 align:middle line:84%
child's attention, but it can
so overstimulate sensitive

00:39:27.770 --> 00:39:31.350 align:middle line:84%
children that they cannot
process the moral lesson behind

00:39:31.350 --> 00:39:33.330 align:middle line:90%
the correction.

00:39:33.330 --> 00:39:35.070 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, you have
to wait until later

00:39:35.070 --> 00:39:38.700 align:middle line:84%
to discuss what happened and
what they should do next time.

00:39:38.700 --> 00:39:39.980 align:middle line:90%
Often, that's all it takes.

00:39:39.980 --> 00:39:42.848 align:middle line:90%


00:39:42.848 --> 00:39:47.380 align:middle line:10%
>> What's interesting is that
the percentage of men and women

00:39:47.380 --> 00:39:49.270 align:middle line:10%
who are highly
sensitive are equal.

00:39:49.270 --> 00:39:51.880 align:middle line:84%
But because in
most cultures, men

00:39:51.880 --> 00:39:54.790 align:middle line:84%
aren't supposed to
show their emotions,

00:39:54.790 --> 00:39:56.680 align:middle line:84%
it's really hard
for sensitive boys.

00:39:56.680 --> 00:40:16.340 align:middle line:90%


00:40:16.340 --> 00:40:18.980 align:middle line:84%
>> I had a father who
was hardcore military.

00:40:18.980 --> 00:40:23.630 align:middle line:10%
And I remember when
I was six years old

00:40:23.630 --> 00:40:26.240 align:middle line:10%
and I had a little fight
in the neighborhood,

00:40:26.240 --> 00:40:28.220 align:middle line:10%
and he locked me out
of the house and said,

00:40:28.220 --> 00:40:30.719 align:middle line:10%
you're not coming back in this
house until you kick his ass.

00:40:30.719 --> 00:40:34.490 align:middle line:84%
So I knew that I had to stand
up and struggle and fight and be

00:40:34.490 --> 00:40:39.660 align:middle line:84%
a man and not really
show a softer side.

00:40:39.660 --> 00:40:44.535 align:middle line:84%
And so I think in his eyes
he had to toughen me up.

00:40:44.535 --> 00:40:46.970 align:middle line:10%
>> Most sensitive
males, especially,

00:40:46.970 --> 00:40:48.950 align:middle line:10%
have a really hard
time growing up,

00:40:48.950 --> 00:40:54.860 align:middle line:10%
because they don't fit in with
the so-called boy code culture.

00:40:54.860 --> 00:40:58.000 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of times
when a boy expresses

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:02.480 align:middle line:84%
with a group of other boys,
oh, I'm afraid of something

00:41:02.480 --> 00:41:06.680 align:middle line:84%
or I'm scared or I'm
sad or I'm anxious,

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:09.970 align:middle line:84%
they get ostracized
and humiliated.

00:41:09.970 --> 00:41:12.800 align:middle line:84%
>> I know what the
problem is, woman.

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:20.640 align:middle line:84%
Whether you do or not, in this
world a man has to be strong.

00:41:20.640 --> 00:41:23.310 align:middle line:84%
Now he needs to defend himself
when he handles himself

00:41:23.310 --> 00:41:24.720 align:middle line:90%
with other boys.

00:41:24.720 --> 00:41:28.002 align:middle line:84%
He needs to get outdoors,
play some sports.

00:41:28.002 --> 00:41:30.810 align:middle line:84%
>> But he does want
to play sports.

00:41:30.810 --> 00:41:33.446 align:middle line:90%
He's interested in track.

00:41:33.446 --> 00:41:35.890 align:middle line:90%
>> Track?

00:41:35.890 --> 00:41:36.690 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:41:36.690 --> 00:41:39.330 align:middle line:84%
So he can learn how to run
away, how to run away faster.

00:41:39.330 --> 00:41:43.170 align:middle line:84%
>> When a parent is not highly
sensitive and does not realize

00:41:43.170 --> 00:41:44.790 align:middle line:84%
that the child is
highly sensitive,

00:41:44.790 --> 00:41:47.220 align:middle line:84%
you will feel that maybe
I have to push him more.

00:41:47.220 --> 00:41:50.410 align:middle line:84%
And when he pushes the child
more, the sensitive child will

00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:53.490 align:middle line:84%
feel, oh, I'm not
accepted like I am,

00:41:53.490 --> 00:41:56.470 align:middle line:84%
He doesn't like me if I
need to have some more time.

00:41:56.470 --> 00:41:58.260 align:middle line:10%
And like that, he
will become more

00:41:58.260 --> 00:42:01.020 align:middle line:10%
unsecure in his
relationship to the father.

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:02.880 align:middle line:10%
And he will maybe
be even less stern

00:42:02.880 --> 00:42:04.070 align:middle line:10%
than he would otherwise be.

00:42:04.070 --> 00:42:06.480 align:middle line:84%
>> My father couldn't
talk about it.

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:08.040 align:middle line:84%
My mother couldn't
talk about it.

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:09.730 align:middle line:10%
We couldn't talk about it.

00:42:09.730 --> 00:42:13.260 align:middle line:10%
And they couldn't
frame it in a way that

00:42:13.260 --> 00:42:15.150 align:middle line:10%
would have been
beneficial for me

00:42:15.150 --> 00:42:18.960 align:middle line:10%
in order for me to understand
myself, understand my emotions,

00:42:18.960 --> 00:42:21.959 align:middle line:10%
and not reacting with
the anger instead.

00:42:21.959 --> 00:42:24.000 align:middle line:84%
Because when you're
frustrated and you can't talk

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.550 align:middle line:90%
about things, you get angry.

00:42:26.550 --> 00:42:29.255 align:middle line:90%
That's how I was raised.

00:42:29.255 --> 00:42:32.470 align:middle line:84%
>> He needs to get in there
and tackle things-- football,

00:42:32.470 --> 00:42:33.570 align:middle line:90%
basketball.

00:42:33.570 --> 00:42:37.255 align:middle line:90%
>> Bill, Bill.

00:42:37.255 --> 00:42:40.150 align:middle line:90%
This isn't you.

00:42:40.150 --> 00:42:43.180 align:middle line:90%
This isn't you.

00:42:43.180 --> 00:42:46.180 align:middle line:84%
Don't you remember
how loving you

00:42:46.180 --> 00:42:49.490 align:middle line:90%
were to him when he was a baby?

00:42:49.490 --> 00:42:53.360 align:middle line:84%
Now he just fears you,
always shouting and hollering

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:55.772 align:middle line:90%
all the time.

00:42:55.772 --> 00:42:58.640 align:middle line:84%
>> For one thing, just think
of the cost of messing up

00:42:58.640 --> 00:43:02.150 align:middle line:84%
a sensitive child because
they're going to have this

00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:05.570 align:middle line:84%
depression anxiety and various
problems their whole lives,

00:43:05.570 --> 00:43:08.750 align:middle line:84%
versus getting it right
and having them being some

00:43:08.750 --> 00:43:12.319 align:middle line:84%
of the most productive,
thoughtful members of society.

00:43:12.319 --> 00:43:13.610 align:middle line:90%
And what do we need in society?

00:43:13.610 --> 00:43:18.340 align:middle line:84%
People who think deeply, have
strong emotional response

00:43:18.340 --> 00:43:19.140 align:middle line:90%
at the same time.

00:43:19.140 --> 00:43:22.490 align:middle line:84%
So we said, good
heart, a deep mind,

00:43:22.490 --> 00:43:25.010 align:middle line:84%
sensitive to subtleties so
they notice what's going on.

00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:28.220 align:middle line:84%
We need more of those
people everywhere.

00:43:28.220 --> 00:43:31.220 align:middle line:84%
One of my favorite stories
of successful parenting

00:43:31.220 --> 00:43:34.730 align:middle line:84%
of a sensitive child is that
of social psychologist Steve

00:43:34.730 --> 00:43:39.100 align:middle line:84%
Wright, a friend and colleague
from Vancouver, Canada,

00:43:39.100 --> 00:43:42.290 align:middle line:84%
a father who is definitely
not highly sensitive himself.

00:43:42.290 --> 00:43:45.645 align:middle line:10%
>> My older daughter is not
a highly sensitive person.

00:43:45.645 --> 00:43:47.270 align:middle line:10%
And so for two years,
I've been dealing

00:43:47.270 --> 00:43:48.894 align:middle line:10%
with this bubbling
baby who just wanted

00:43:48.894 --> 00:43:50.300 align:middle line:10%
to go out and be everywhere.

00:43:50.300 --> 00:43:55.265 align:middle line:84%
And then Reesa showed up and
things were very different.

00:43:55.265 --> 00:43:57.740 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi, I wanted to go there.

00:43:57.740 --> 00:43:58.730 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

00:43:58.730 --> 00:43:59.530 align:middle line:90%
Good-bye.

00:43:59.530 --> 00:44:01.700 align:middle line:84%
>> I wondered what
we were doing wrong.

00:44:01.700 --> 00:44:03.630 align:middle line:90%
I wondered why she wasn't happy.

00:44:03.630 --> 00:44:05.390 align:middle line:84%
I wondered why she
was scared of people,

00:44:05.390 --> 00:44:08.570 align:middle line:84%
or at least I thought
she was scared of people.

00:44:08.570 --> 00:44:11.780 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, it was
difficult in the sense

00:44:11.780 --> 00:44:15.595 align:middle line:84%
of feeling like that
she was sad too much,

00:44:15.595 --> 00:44:16.970 align:middle line:84%
or that she was
worried too much,

00:44:16.970 --> 00:44:20.420 align:middle line:84%
or that she wasn't happy about
the things that we were doing,

00:44:20.420 --> 00:44:21.920 align:middle line:84%
or that I was doing
things that were

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:25.580 align:middle line:84%
making her feel unsafe or feel
sad or scared or whatever.

00:44:25.580 --> 00:44:30.470 align:middle line:84%
>> When I was younger, it was
really hard for me to make

00:44:30.470 --> 00:44:31.550 align:middle line:90%
friends.

00:44:31.550 --> 00:44:34.400 align:middle line:10%
And because I wouldn't
want to be the first person

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:36.920 align:middle line:10%
to go and talk to someone.

00:44:36.920 --> 00:44:41.540 align:middle line:10%
And if the other person
was shy or more reserved,

00:44:41.540 --> 00:44:42.800 align:middle line:10%
I wouldn't go up to them.

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:45.140 align:middle line:10%
I would wait for people
to come and talk to me.

00:44:45.140 --> 00:44:48.590 align:middle line:84%
>> The big thing for Reesa was
that when we go to new places,

00:44:48.590 --> 00:44:49.580 align:middle line:90%
she needed time.

00:44:49.580 --> 00:44:52.280 align:middle line:84%
>> My dad is the
complete opposite to me.

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:55.550 align:middle line:84%
He's really encouraging
me to do things and always

00:44:55.550 --> 00:44:56.550 align:middle line:90%
in a positive way.

00:44:56.550 --> 00:44:58.820 align:middle line:84%
But for me, sometimes,
it's too much.

00:44:58.820 --> 00:44:59.750 align:middle line:90%
>> No.

00:44:59.750 --> 00:45:02.040 align:middle line:84%
>> So that was really
hard on me, too,

00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:05.540 align:middle line:84%
because then I felt as if I
was letting them down and I

00:45:05.540 --> 00:45:09.470 align:middle line:84%
wasn't stepping up, and I wasn't
putting myself out there and I

00:45:09.470 --> 00:45:10.700 align:middle line:90%
wasn't talking to everybody.

00:45:10.700 --> 00:45:14.640 align:middle line:84%
So I felt really bad on myself,
and it was really hard on me.

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:18.042 align:middle line:90%


00:45:18.042 --> 00:45:21.980 align:middle line:84%
>> It was a really good
learning lesson for me.

00:45:21.980 --> 00:45:26.520 align:middle line:84%
Reesa is not like me, and that
that's perfectly all right.

00:45:26.520 --> 00:45:28.640 align:middle line:84%
And that's a really
good way to be.

00:45:28.640 --> 00:45:32.240 align:middle line:84%
And here I had been doing
all these things like,

00:45:32.240 --> 00:45:34.890 align:middle line:84%
talk to the man, come on, say
hello, tell him your name.

00:45:34.890 --> 00:45:37.730 align:middle line:84%
Or, shake her hand or give
her a hug or whatever.

00:45:37.730 --> 00:45:40.010 align:middle line:84%
And I realized this is
just totally unfair.

00:45:40.010 --> 00:45:43.760 align:middle line:84%
>> So for both of us, we have
to stop and think about how

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:47.430 align:middle line:84%
the other person sees things,
and we have to work together,

00:45:47.430 --> 00:45:52.020 align:middle line:84%
talk it out, and say, I feel
like this, I know how you feel,

00:45:52.020 --> 00:45:53.300 align:middle line:90%
but this is how I feel.

00:45:53.300 --> 00:45:55.550 align:middle line:84%
So we both have to
talk and we both have

00:45:55.550 --> 00:45:57.830 align:middle line:84%
to express our sides
of it for us to be

00:45:57.830 --> 00:46:00.550 align:middle line:90%
able to get through things.

00:46:00.550 --> 00:46:03.860 align:middle line:84%
>> So some parents learn early
to understand their sensitive

00:46:03.860 --> 00:46:08.630 align:middle line:84%
child and adapt their parenting,
even if with some difficulty.

00:46:08.630 --> 00:46:10.710 align:middle line:84%
Others are more
threatened by the idea.

00:46:10.710 --> 00:46:12.705 align:middle line:90%
>> So what's up, Mrs. Wilbur?

00:46:12.705 --> 00:46:16.580 align:middle line:84%
>> Your son seems
a little withdrawn,

00:46:16.580 --> 00:46:19.694 align:middle line:90%
maybe even depressed.

00:46:19.694 --> 00:46:22.135 align:middle line:84%
>> He needs to learn to
stand up for himself.

00:46:22.135 --> 00:46:23.600 align:middle line:90%
>> Maybe.

00:46:23.600 --> 00:46:26.020 align:middle line:84%
It could be-- or
I wondered if he

00:46:26.020 --> 00:46:29.602 align:middle line:84%
was one of those kids
that was born sensitive.

00:46:29.602 --> 00:46:31.960 align:middle line:90%
>> Sensitive?

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:35.250 align:middle line:84%
Great, that's all I need
is to be labeled sensitive.

00:46:35.250 --> 00:46:37.246 align:middle line:90%
It sounds like a girl.

00:46:37.246 --> 00:46:40.325 align:middle line:84%
>> There's just as many boys
as there are girls that are

00:46:40.325 --> 00:46:41.125 align:middle line:90%
sensitive.

00:46:41.125 --> 00:46:44.398 align:middle line:90%
>> They call it something else.

00:46:44.398 --> 00:46:47.310 align:middle line:90%
>> Let's call it, Bill.

00:46:47.310 --> 00:46:51.080 align:middle line:84%
Look, I'm going to
say something now.

00:46:51.080 --> 00:46:54.890 align:middle line:84%
Bill, I think you're
highly sensitive yourself--

00:46:54.890 --> 00:46:57.790 align:middle line:90%
emotional, irritable at times.

00:46:57.790 --> 00:47:01.270 align:middle line:90%


00:47:01.270 --> 00:47:06.220 align:middle line:84%
You're a perfectionist,
always deep in thought.

00:47:06.220 --> 00:47:08.045 align:middle line:90%
You want to be your own boss.

00:47:08.045 --> 00:47:11.950 align:middle line:84%
I know it's what
attracted me to you.

00:47:11.950 --> 00:47:14.490 align:middle line:84%
And I know now that you're
just worried that Hank

00:47:14.490 --> 00:47:17.430 align:middle line:90%
is going to be like you.

00:47:17.430 --> 00:47:20.440 align:middle line:84%
And you want him to
cover it up, like you

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:24.052 align:middle line:90%
have been your entire life.

00:47:24.052 --> 00:47:28.440 align:middle line:84%
>> Differential susceptibility
causes some children to be more

00:47:28.440 --> 00:47:31.060 align:middle line:84%
affected than others
by their environment,

00:47:31.060 --> 00:47:33.523 align:middle line:90%
both positively and negatively.

00:47:33.523 --> 00:47:41.420 align:middle line:90%


00:47:41.420 --> 00:47:43.760 align:middle line:84%
And the same differential
susceptibility

00:47:43.760 --> 00:47:45.710 align:middle line:90%
occurs in the work environment.

00:47:45.710 --> 00:47:49.340 align:middle line:84%
Some work environments bring out
the best in sensitive people,

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:51.860 align:middle line:90%
some definitely don't.

00:47:51.860 --> 00:47:53.600 align:middle line:84%
This can cause
some organizations

00:47:53.600 --> 00:47:55.730 align:middle line:90%
to lose their best employees.

00:47:55.730 --> 00:47:58.050 align:middle line:84%
And society failed to make
use of one of its greatest

00:47:58.050 --> 00:47:58.850 align:middle line:90%
strengths.

00:47:58.850 --> 00:48:03.850 align:middle line:90%


00:48:03.850 --> 00:48:06.820 align:middle line:84%
I sort of say that
workplaces are like families.

00:48:06.820 --> 00:48:09.226 align:middle line:84%
There are good ones
and not very good ones.

00:48:09.226 --> 00:48:10.600 align:middle line:84%
And sensitive
people are bothered

00:48:10.600 --> 00:48:15.850 align:middle line:84%
more by abusive supervisors
or just negative supervisors

00:48:15.850 --> 00:48:17.980 align:middle line:90%
or negative coworkers.

00:48:17.980 --> 00:48:24.190 align:middle line:84%
And so they end up needing to
quit, and they have to quit.

00:48:24.190 --> 00:48:27.070 align:middle line:90%


00:48:27.070 --> 00:48:29.430 align:middle line:84%
Of course, the one problem
for the highly sensitive

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:33.280 align:middle line:84%
is being easily overstimulated,
especially at work.

00:48:33.280 --> 00:48:35.530 align:middle line:84%
One study found that
supervisors were

00:48:35.530 --> 00:48:38.725 align:middle line:84%
most pleased with their
highly sensitive workers.

00:48:38.725 --> 00:48:40.075 align:middle line:90%
>> Yep, I'll be there.

00:48:40.075 --> 00:48:44.530 align:middle line:84%
>> But these workers themselves
had the lowest well-being.

00:48:44.530 --> 00:48:48.190 align:middle line:10%
>> When there are negative
events that are occurring,

00:48:48.190 --> 00:48:52.120 align:middle line:10%
highly sensitive persons tend to
react in a very overstimulated

00:48:52.120 --> 00:48:55.562 align:middle line:10%
fashion, because we absorb that
negativity much more deeply

00:48:55.562 --> 00:48:57.020 align:middle line:10%
than a non-highly
sensitive person.

00:48:57.020 --> 00:49:01.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Since some corporate cultures
or individual managers may not

00:49:01.900 --> 00:49:04.840 align:middle line:84%
yet have realized the importance
of supporting their sensitive

00:49:04.840 --> 00:49:08.590 align:middle line:84%
employees' needs, these
employees themselves must do

00:49:08.590 --> 00:49:10.820 align:middle line:84%
what they can to
prevent burnout,

00:49:10.820 --> 00:49:13.480 align:middle line:84%
which often requires
standing up for themselves,

00:49:13.480 --> 00:49:16.780 align:middle line:84%
because they usually
are highly valued.

00:49:16.780 --> 00:49:19.810 align:middle line:84%
And generally they need
to be careful about taking

00:49:19.810 --> 00:49:21.340 align:middle line:90%
good care of themselves.

00:49:21.340 --> 00:49:27.208 align:middle line:90%


00:49:27.208 --> 00:49:30.390 align:middle line:84%
>> But If we don't
practice really a rigorous,

00:49:30.390 --> 00:49:33.290 align:middle line:84%
almost religious
form of self-care,

00:49:33.290 --> 00:49:37.310 align:middle line:84%
we really set ourselves up
for a number of health issues,

00:49:37.310 --> 00:49:40.880 align:middle line:84%
number of behavioral issues, a
number of emotional issues that

00:49:40.880 --> 00:49:43.595 align:middle line:84%
can affect our entire lives,
our entire sense of well-being.

00:49:43.595 --> 00:49:46.040 align:middle line:84%
>> The world gets
more high-paced,

00:49:46.040 --> 00:49:47.760 align:middle line:84%
it seems like they
can't keep up.

00:49:47.760 --> 00:49:49.940 align:middle line:84%
But they actually
can't keep up, as long

00:49:49.940 --> 00:49:53.570 align:middle line:84%
as they get the few things they
need in the workplace, which

00:49:53.570 --> 00:49:56.390 align:middle line:84%
is a little bit
of peace and quiet

00:49:56.390 --> 00:50:02.030 align:middle line:84%
and a little bit of
positive reinforcement,

00:50:02.030 --> 00:50:04.580 align:middle line:84%
because sensitive
people by nature

00:50:04.580 --> 00:50:08.670 align:middle line:84%
pick up on criticism so that
they can revise their behavior

00:50:08.670 --> 00:50:09.470 align:middle line:90%
and do better.

00:50:09.470 --> 00:50:11.600 align:middle line:84%
But if all they
get is criticism,

00:50:11.600 --> 00:50:15.500 align:middle line:84%
pretty soon they just
feel beaten down.

00:50:15.500 --> 00:50:17.750 align:middle line:84%
What I have noticed
about sensitive people

00:50:17.750 --> 00:50:20.540 align:middle line:84%
is that they do switch jobs,
sometimes whole careers.

00:50:20.540 --> 00:50:23.285 align:middle line:84%
Very often, they decide
to be self-employed.

00:50:23.285 --> 00:50:25.820 align:middle line:10%
>> For the beginning
of my career,

00:50:25.820 --> 00:50:27.530 align:middle line:10%
I always worked
for other people.

00:50:27.530 --> 00:50:29.870 align:middle line:10%
I was in an office
and I couldn't

00:50:29.870 --> 00:50:31.520 align:middle line:10%
stand to be in an office.

00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:34.280 align:middle line:10%
I couldn't stand the lighting, I
couldn't stand being cooped up,

00:50:34.280 --> 00:50:36.560 align:middle line:10%
I couldn't stand so many people.

00:50:36.560 --> 00:50:39.680 align:middle line:10%
And eventually, I
realized I really

00:50:39.680 --> 00:50:42.560 align:middle line:10%
need to find something
that I can do at home.

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:46.580 align:middle line:84%
And my husband and I were
going back and forth, saying,

00:50:46.580 --> 00:50:49.610 align:middle line:84%
you know how can we do
something together as a couple,

00:50:49.610 --> 00:50:53.480 align:middle line:84%
and do something that will
help change the world, which

00:50:53.480 --> 00:50:54.820 align:middle line:90%
was a big thought.

00:50:54.820 --> 00:50:58.370 align:middle line:84%
But we really took it to task,
and DailyOM was born of that.

00:50:58.370 --> 00:51:06.590 align:middle line:90%


00:51:06.590 --> 00:51:09.730 align:middle line:84%
>> I so much enjoyed
meeting John Hughes.

00:51:09.730 --> 00:51:13.460 align:middle line:84%
He is such a perfect example
of a sensitive man triumphing

00:51:13.460 --> 00:51:15.710 align:middle line:90%
over adverse conditions.

00:51:15.710 --> 00:51:18.470 align:middle line:10%
In his case, a dominating
father who squelched all

00:51:18.470 --> 00:51:21.766 align:middle line:10%
emotion in himself and his son.

00:51:21.766 --> 00:51:24.830 align:middle line:84%
John has spent years
finding his true self.

00:51:24.830 --> 00:51:29.140 align:middle line:84%
But along the way, he became a
leader in the business world.

00:51:29.140 --> 00:51:30.309 align:middle line:10%
>> After a few years--

00:51:30.309 --> 00:51:32.350 align:middle line:10%
not even a few years,
probably 20-something years

00:51:32.350 --> 00:51:33.150 align:middle line:10%
of my career--

00:51:33.150 --> 00:51:36.940 align:middle line:10%
changing jobs every two to three
years, what I finally realized

00:51:36.940 --> 00:51:41.020 align:middle line:10%
is that channeling
that sensitivity

00:51:41.020 --> 00:51:44.380 align:middle line:10%
and that drive to kind
of craft my own career,

00:51:44.380 --> 00:51:46.060 align:middle line:10%
that's really what I was after.

00:51:46.060 --> 00:51:49.460 align:middle line:84%
I get to make a huge impact
in a short period of time.

00:51:49.460 --> 00:51:55.000 align:middle line:84%
I'm not locked into one company,
one management or leadership

00:51:55.000 --> 00:51:56.980 align:middle line:90%
style within a company.

00:51:56.980 --> 00:52:00.070 align:middle line:84%
And I can pick and
choose my clients.

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:02.830 align:middle line:10%
And there's a freedom,
there's a huge risk

00:52:02.830 --> 00:52:04.690 align:middle line:10%
in being out on my own.

00:52:04.690 --> 00:52:07.180 align:middle line:10%
But at the same time, there's
a huge freedom as well.

00:52:07.180 --> 00:52:10.150 align:middle line:10%
And the freedom is what
I just absolutely love.

00:52:10.150 --> 00:52:12.070 align:middle line:10%
And so I guess what
I've really done

00:52:12.070 --> 00:52:16.570 align:middle line:10%
is take my drive and my
desires and my sensitivities

00:52:16.570 --> 00:52:21.270 align:middle line:10%
and I've been able to craft
a career that fits me to a T

00:52:21.270 --> 00:52:25.270 align:middle line:10%
>> John Hughes has been such a
successful CIO that he is now

00:52:25.270 --> 00:52:28.840 align:middle line:10%
in demand as an interim CIO,
while helping companies find

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:32.110 align:middle line:10%
the right one, as
well as coaching CIOs.

00:52:32.110 --> 00:52:35.140 align:middle line:84%
He recently published a highly
praised book on leadership,

00:52:35.140 --> 00:52:37.510 align:middle line:90%
"Haunting the CEO."

00:52:37.510 --> 00:52:40.750 align:middle line:84%
In an article on why
HSPs make good leaders,

00:52:40.750 --> 00:52:43.750 align:middle line:84%
he says they miss nothing,
while falling back

00:52:43.750 --> 00:52:45.430 align:middle line:90%
to let team members shine.

00:52:45.430 --> 00:52:47.200 align:middle line:10%
And they have almost
an innate ability

00:52:47.200 --> 00:52:51.160 align:middle line:10%
to say and do the right
thing at just the right time.

00:52:51.160 --> 00:52:53.830 align:middle line:10%
His observations about
highly sensitive leaders

00:52:53.830 --> 00:52:57.550 align:middle line:10%
in the corporate environment are
similar to those of Dr. Maike

00:52:57.550 --> 00:53:00.190 align:middle line:10%
Andresen, a professor
in the renowned business

00:53:00.190 --> 00:53:02.770 align:middle line:10%
school at Bamberg
University in Germany,

00:53:02.770 --> 00:53:04.170 align:middle line:10%
and highly sensitive herself.

00:53:04.170 --> 00:53:08.190 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING GERMAN]

00:53:08.190 --> 00:53:13.420 align:middle line:90%


00:53:13.420 --> 00:53:15.610 align:middle line:10%
I did some research about
highly sensitive person

00:53:15.610 --> 00:53:18.730 align:middle line:10%
regarding the motivation
to become a leader.

00:53:18.730 --> 00:53:22.720 align:middle line:10%
And I wanted to know whether a
highly sensitive person would

00:53:22.720 --> 00:53:25.230 align:middle line:10%
de-select themselves
from this role.

00:53:25.230 --> 00:53:28.590 align:middle line:10%
And what I found out so far
is that this is not the case.

00:53:28.590 --> 00:53:29.770 align:middle line:10%
So which is good.

00:53:29.770 --> 00:53:35.222 align:middle line:10%
So it's not that they fear or
are afraid to become a leader,

00:53:35.222 --> 00:53:37.090 align:middle line:10%
and I think there
are some strengths

00:53:37.090 --> 00:53:39.550 align:middle line:10%
that highly sensitive
leaders have.

00:53:39.550 --> 00:53:44.275 align:middle line:10%
So now the question is how they
can get into these positions.

00:53:44.275 --> 00:53:49.320 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING GERMAN]

00:53:49.320 --> 00:53:53.200 align:middle line:10%
>> Dr. Andresen helps
corporations notice and use

00:53:53.200 --> 00:53:56.620 align:middle line:10%
the strengths of highly
sensitive persons to create

00:53:56.620 --> 00:53:59.440 align:middle line:10%
an environment
that benefits both.

00:53:59.440 --> 00:54:01.510 align:middle line:84%
Such an environment
has been created

00:54:01.510 --> 00:54:05.980 align:middle line:84%
by the CEO Rupert Mayer of the
leading orchid growing company,

00:54:05.980 --> 00:54:07.960 align:middle line:84%
a family-owned
business in Germany.

00:54:07.960 --> 00:54:11.450 align:middle line:84%
>> When I worked together
with Rupert Mayer,

00:54:11.450 --> 00:54:18.490 align:middle line:84%
I was astonished to see how
sensitive he is and how well he

00:54:18.490 --> 00:54:20.620 align:middle line:90%
perceives his employees.

00:54:20.620 --> 00:54:24.400 align:middle line:84%
He has a very detailed view
about their personality.

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:25.240 align:middle line:90%
And I was amazed.

00:54:25.240 --> 00:54:26.675 align:middle line:90%
I never saw that among managers.

00:54:26.675 --> 00:54:29.140 align:middle line:84%
So he is really
sensitive himself.

00:54:29.140 --> 00:54:30.710 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING GERMAN]

00:54:30.710 --> 00:54:35.710 align:middle line:84%
>> So whenever
there are problems,

00:54:35.710 --> 00:54:41.380 align:middle line:84%
he is very good at detecting
these problems and in finding

00:54:41.380 --> 00:54:45.070 align:middle line:84%
the reasons, and then also in
finding good solutions in order

00:54:45.070 --> 00:54:46.905 align:middle line:84%
to solve these
challenges they have.

00:54:46.905 --> 00:54:49.190 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING GERMAN]

00:54:49.190 --> 00:54:54.050 align:middle line:10%
>> In order to survive as a
manager on a long-term basis,

00:54:54.050 --> 00:54:57.550 align:middle line:10%
I think it is very important
these days to have a technical

00:54:57.550 --> 00:55:01.570 align:middle line:10%
competence, a social competence,
and sensitivity towards

00:55:01.570 --> 00:55:05.250 align:middle line:10%
colleagues who are considered
to be highly sensitive.

00:55:05.250 --> 00:55:07.480 align:middle line:10%
And that's a part of
social competence.

00:55:07.480 --> 00:55:09.265 align:middle line:10%
>> [SPEAKING GERMAN]

00:55:09.265 --> 00:55:11.880 align:middle line:84%
>> When we communicate this
concept of high sensitivity,

00:55:11.880 --> 00:55:13.570 align:middle line:90%
I think there is one danger.

00:55:13.570 --> 00:55:16.750 align:middle line:84%
And the danger is
that people think

00:55:16.750 --> 00:55:19.750 align:middle line:84%
that we want to do
something for a minority,

00:55:19.750 --> 00:55:24.010 align:middle line:84%
and that they need special care
and special treatment, which

00:55:24.010 --> 00:55:24.850 align:middle line:90%
is not the case.

00:55:24.850 --> 00:55:29.530 align:middle line:84%
Because it is just a trait,
and some 20% have this trait,

00:55:29.530 --> 00:55:32.320 align:middle line:84%
and the 80% do not
have this trait.

00:55:32.320 --> 00:55:36.310 align:middle line:10%
And for me, it's more
a question of profiting

00:55:36.310 --> 00:55:40.610 align:middle line:10%
from the strengths of both
groups and to combine people,

00:55:40.610 --> 00:55:45.770 align:middle line:10%
and so that we can profit
from each other's personality

00:55:45.770 --> 00:55:46.570 align:middle line:10%
traits.

00:55:46.570 --> 00:55:49.265 align:middle line:90%


00:55:49.265 --> 00:55:52.630 align:middle line:84%
>> Certainly, the needs of
the highly sensitive require

00:55:52.630 --> 00:55:56.290 align:middle line:84%
attention if they're going
to stay in companies.

00:55:56.290 --> 00:55:58.330 align:middle line:84%
But both research
and the experience

00:55:58.330 --> 00:56:00.700 align:middle line:84%
of some business
people teaches us

00:56:00.700 --> 00:56:03.430 align:middle line:84%
that organizations
need both types.

00:56:03.430 --> 00:56:07.930 align:middle line:84%
How can we all work together--
parenting, in organizations,

00:56:07.930 --> 00:56:09.580 align:middle line:90%
or in marriage?

00:56:09.580 --> 00:56:13.510 align:middle line:84%
First, the highly sensitive must
value themselves so that they

00:56:13.510 --> 00:56:17.020 align:middle line:84%
can balance the other
80% and do their part,

00:56:17.020 --> 00:56:18.640 align:middle line:90%
their own particular part.

00:56:18.640 --> 00:56:28.580 align:middle line:90%


00:56:28.580 --> 00:56:31.990 align:middle line:84%
So what I want to know
is, what you teach

00:56:31.990 --> 00:56:33.730 align:middle line:90%
HSPs is about being empowered.

00:56:33.730 --> 00:56:34.835 align:middle line:10%
What do they need to know?

00:56:34.835 --> 00:56:37.550 align:middle line:10%
>> Oh great, that's
such a great question.

00:56:37.550 --> 00:56:40.160 align:middle line:10%
It's come to me over the years
sort of this metaphor of,

00:56:40.160 --> 00:56:43.610 align:middle line:10%
here we are in San
Francisco and California

00:56:43.610 --> 00:56:45.320 align:middle line:10%
and it's Highway 101--

